20
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:04,170
Only much longer.

21
00:01:04,170 --> 00:01:07,369
And less of a mutually agreed-upon decision.

22
00:01:07,369 --> 00:01:10,439
Because, according to the South China Morning
Post,

23
00:01:10,439 --> 00:01:13,920
Chinese scientists are planning the world’s
longest train tunnel...

24
00:01:13,920 --> 00:01:17,509
to connect mainland China to Taiwan.

25
00:01:17,509 --> 00:01:22,789
Rumor has it, the Chinese Communist Party
absolutely adores the plan!

26
00:01:22,789 --> 00:01:24,170
So much so, in fact,

27
00:01:24,170 --> 00:01:28,649
they’re ready to start planning without
Taiwan’s cooperation.

28
00:01:28,649 --> 00:01:30,829
Researchers told the South China Morning Post
that

29
00:01:30,829 --> 00:01:33,980
“it’s possible Beijing would start work
on the project

30
00:01:33,980 --> 00:01:38,039
in a unilateral and largely symbolic move.”

31
00:01:38,039 --> 00:01:40,770
The 84-mile Taiwan Strait Tunnel

32
00:01:40,770 --> 00:01:43,190
would link Pingtan in Mainland China...

33
00:01:43,190 --> 00:01:45,869
...to Hsinchu in Taiwan.

34
00:01:45,869 --> 00:01:50,260
And yes, Hsinchu happens to be where Taiwan
has an army base—

35
00:01:50,260 --> 00:01:52,929
where forces train hard to prepare for an
aggressive,

36
00:01:52,929 --> 00:01:55,760
unannounced visit by the People’s Liberation
Army.

37
00:01:55,760 --> 00:01:58,020
Otherwise known as an invasion.

38
00:01:58,020 --> 00:02:01,289
So there’s a good chance that Taiwan might
react negatively

39
00:02:01,289 --> 00:02:04,640
if members of a Chinese tunnel drilling team
start to

40
00:02:04,640 --> 00:02:07,270
pop up out of the ground unannounced.

41
00:02:07,270 --> 00:02:09,800
But due to engineering constraints, a tunnel
this long

42
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:13,849
